    <string name="gui_generator_intro"><![CDATA[This is the siteswap generator component of Juggling Lab. It finds juggling
patterns in a generalized form of siteswap notation. For a full description of
this notation and the program's operation, consult the documentation at
https://jugglinglab.org. All patterns satisfying the given constraints are
listed by the program. Solo asynchronous juggling is the default mode.

Usage:   gen <number> <max throw> <period> [options]

where options include:
  -n             show number of patterns
  -no            print number only
  -se            hide starting/ending sequences for excited state patterns

  -x <regex> ..  exclude listed regular expressions
  -i <regex> ..  must include listed regular expressions
  -lame          remove '11' sequence in async mode

  -g             ground state patterns only
  -ng            excited state patterns only
  -f             full listing (including composite patterns)
  -prime         prime patterns only
  -rot           show all rotated versions of patterns (e.g., 645 and 564)

  -m <number>    multiplexing with at most <number> simultaneous throws
  -mf            allow simultaneous nontrivial catches (squeeze patterns)
  -mc            disallow multiplex clustered throws (e.g., [33])
  -mt            require at least one multiplexed throw with no holds

  -s             find synchronous siteswaps

  -j <number>    set number of jugglers
  -cp            show only connected passing patterns
  -sym           show only juggler-symmetric passing patterns
  -group         group throws by juggler in passing patterns
  -d <number>    passing communication delay (see docs)
  -l <number>    passing leader person number (for use with -d)
  -jp            show patterns with all juggler permutations

Note: The value for <max throw> can be omitted by using the value '-', in which
case throw values are unbounded. Also <period> may be specified as a range,
like '1-5' or '-5' or '-'.

Examples:
  gen 5 7 5
  gen 5 7 1-5 -x 2 3
  gen 5 7 - -prime -n
  gen 4 - 3 -f -rot -no
  gen 4 6 6 -s -g
  gen 5 6 4 -m 2 -g -mt
  gen 6 4 2 -j 2 -g -jp -m 2 -d 1 -l 1]]></string>
    <string name="gui_transitioner_intro"><![CDATA[This is the siteswap transition-finding component of Juggling Lab. It finds
transitions between any two siteswap patterns, as long as the number of objects
and jugglers are consistent.

Transitions are not unique. The program handles this by generating a variety of
options for the transition from A to B, but only a single (minimal) transition
from B back to A.

Usage:   trans <pattern A> <pattern B> [-options]

where options include:
  -m <number>    multiplexing with at most <number> simultaneous throws
  -mf            allow simultaneous nontrivial catches (squeeze patterns)
  -mc            disallow multiplex clustered throws (e.g., [33])
  -limits        turn off limits on run time and pattern count

Examples:
  trans 5 771
  trans 5 771 -m 2
  trans 645 '(6x,4)*'
  trans '<33|22>' '<55|00>']]></string>
    <string name="gui_cli_help1"><![CDATA[This is the command line interface to Juggling Lab. Recognized options:

   jlab start
      Launches the application.

   jlab open <file1.jml> <file2.jml> ...
      Launches the application and opens the listed JML files.

   jlab anim <pattern> [-prefs <prefs>]
      Opens a window with an animation of the given pattern, using the
      given (optional) animation preferences.

   jlab gen <gen_options> [-out <path>]
      Runs the siteswap generator and prints a list of patterns, using the
      given set of generator options to define the number of objects, etc.
      Type "jlab gen" with no options for a help message. The output may
      optionally be written to a file.

   jlab trans <pattern A> <pattern B> [-options] [-out <path>]
      Runs the siteswap transition-finder and prints a list of transitions
      from pattern A to pattern B. Type "jlab trans" for a help message. The
      output may optionally be written to a file.

   jlab togif <pattern> [-prefs <prefs>] -out <path>
      Saves a pattern animation to a file as an animated GIF, using the
      given (optional) animation preferences.

   jlab tojml <pattern> [-out <path>]
      Converts a pattern to JML notation, Juggling Lab's internal XML-based
      pattern description. This may optionally be written to a file.

   jlab verify [-tojml] <file1.jml> <file2.jml> ... [-out <path>]
      Checks the validity of the listed JML files. For pattern list files, the
      validity of each line within the list is verified. The output may
      optionally be written to a file.

Pattern input:
   <pattern> can take one of three formats:

   1. A pattern in siteswap notation, for example 771 or (6x,4)(4,6x).
   2. A siteswap pattern annotated with additional settings, in a semi-
      colon separated format. This is described in more detail at
      https://jugglinglab.org/html/sspanel.html
   3. A JML pattern read in from a file, using the format '-jml <path>'.

Animation preferences input:
   <prefs> are optional and are used to override Juggling Lab's default
   preferences. These are given in a semicolon-separated format. See
   https://jugglinglab.org/html/animinfo.html

NOTE: Care should be taken when using characters that may be interpreted in
special ways by the command line interpreter. On Windows use double quotes
around settings to avoid confusion, and single quotes on macOS/Unix.

]]></string>
    <string name="gui_cli_help2"><![CDATA[Examples:
   jlab anim '(6x,4)*'
   jlab togif 'pattern=3;dwell=1.0;bps=4.0;hands=(-30)(2.5).(30)(-2.5).(-30)(0).' -out mills.gif
   jlab anim -jml my_favorite_pattern.jml
   jlab anim 771 -prefs 'stereo=true;width=800;height=600'
   jlab anim 5B -prefs 'bouncesound=true'
   jlab gen 5 7 5
   jlab trans 5 771]]></string>
